    INTRODUCTION:
  


       Putting your Amiga 1200 in a tower case isn't just a hope
now. There are different ways to get a good A1200T or A1200Desk-
Top,  and of course you can do that  spending much money or not.
One of the most expensive way is buying one of those 1200 upgra-
de kits which can make your 1200 a Tower. An italian dealer, DB-
Line, sells the Micronik Invinitiv Tower and, with five Zorro II
slots, costs about $900. 
       What I wanted to do was spending as less as possible  and
get a good solution too for my beloved A1200.  It requires a bit
of work from you, though.
       If you are still reading, then you are really  interested
and so you still didn't get a wonderful A1200T. Now I got a 1200
Tower with a Blizzard 1260, 16Mb Ram, 2 hard disks (420M and 1.6
Gb) and a poor Triniton TV which allows a quite clear interlaced
NTSC screen. Everything I miss is a good monitor and a gfx card.
In fact I'm thinking to get a CyberVision 3D for my 1200. That's 
not a mad idea, 'cause there are at least 2 dealers that sells a
Z2 or Z3 daughterboard for the A1200, and they are Eagle and Mi-
cronik (both in Germany). The new Z3 Micronik card will be abso-
lutely wonderful. It comes with 5 Zorro3 slots, 2 or 3 PCI slots
and a SCSI controller (fastest than any A1200  accelerator board
SCSI kit). Then it will have the usual A1200 CPU duplicator  (so
you can always use your old accelerator board) and also an A4000
CPU slot and a video slot. So you can also use a A3/4000 accele-
rator board such the CyberStorm MkII with a PowerUp PPC 604. 
       Anyways, here's what you have to do to get your A1200T.



    WHY YOU SHOULD DO IT:
    
    
       1 - You can put a hard disk (or the hard disks)  and your
           CD reader in a more reliable place than your  dustish
           desk.
           
       2 - You won't ever have all those horrible cables exiting
           from your  A1200 and growing all over your desk,  but
           just one cable from your keyboard to a tower case.
           
       3 - You can put many Z2 or 3 cards in your A1200 buying a
           daughterboard.
           
       4 - You can use those accelerator boards for  A1200 which 
           have some cooling problems.
               
       5 - If you will ever decide to buy a SCSI controller, you
           will know where to put every peripheral you  will get 
           then (Zip, Jaz, Hard Disks, Streamers, and so on).
       
       6 - Your A1200 won't be ever as before and, in  my honest
           opinion, will be cooler. 
           
           
           
    LOOKING FOR STUFF TO USE:
    
    
       This is everything you need to build your A1200 Tower  in
all its parts. Well, I hope I wrote everything I did when  I did 
it last year. If I forgot something, I also hope you  will be so
good to forgive me:


       1 - A good tower case box. You can also use a desktop ca-
           se, but I didn't find anything suitable for my A1200. 
           Maybe you will be luckier. I used a slim tower and it 
           isn't so big, but my A1200 motherboard fits properly. 
           Everything I can suggest you is that you have to find 
           the RIGHT case so one which is right for you  and for 
           your Amiga.
       
       2 - About two meters of 50 poles plain cable. You need it
           to attach all the Amiga ports to the tower rear side. 
           All these cables aren't really  usefull if you decide
           to put the motherboard vertically and so making holes
           in your tower box. Personally, I fit my A1200 mother-
           board orizontally and then I built every cable needed 
           to have them all out of the tower.

       3 - Lots of connectors (if you are using my method).  You 
           will need four 25 pin connectors for the parallel and 
           the serial port (2 female and 2 male connectors). For 
           the same reason,  you will need four 9 pin connectors 
           for the  joystick and the mouse ports.  Then you pro-
           bably could have  problems looking for a female and a 
           male 23pin connector for the video port, because it's 
           not a standard and only Commodore (grr!!) used it for 
           a computer.  Even if you will find it it's almost im-
           possible you'll find it also crimpable like the other 
           ones.  Another problem could be to find  a POWER con-
           nector. In fact also that one isn't a standard and so 
           I used a broken power supply  (A500's) to connect the 
           new PC 250 watt PSU to the A1200.  For the video port 
           problem I  didn't do anything because  I didn't  find 
           any connector yet and because I'm surely going to buy 
           a graphic card or a new Amiga (A\Box???) machine. Now 
           my  video cable from Amiga to the TV is directly con-
           nected to the REAL port of the A1200.

       4 - A new disk drive (the one from the A2/3/4000s, also a
           high density 1.76 Mb drive, if you want), or just the 
           old  one with a PC drive  mask on it.  I had to adapt 
           the PC  drive mask because  it  didn't fit the  Amiga 
           drive. 

       5 - Some resistences for leds, because if you attach them 
           directly with the HD and drive amiga output they will 
           burn in hours.

       6 - Wire cables, very small ones, and bigger ones.  These 
           ones to connect the leds and some pin of the keyboard 
           connector. You can use them also to do a power switch 
           ('cause, you'll see, the normal keyboard reset (Ctrl-
           A-A won't reset anymore).

       7 - A A1/2/3/4000 or CDTV/CD32 Keyboard. You can also use 
           an A500  keyboard, but it isn't really good  for this 
           work, even though works really good. 

       8 - A female DIN  (A2000/A3000) keyboard  connector  or a 
           miniDIN (or PS2 if you like, those one used in IBM PC 
           and in some other machine like Suns)  for A4000, CDTV 
           or CD32.  If you find an A1000 keyboard, don't worry! 
           It's quite easy to find a telephone like connector!

       9 - Screwdrivers, mono  and bi-adesive  narrow, screws, a 
           soldering iron.



    THE KEYBOARD PROBLEM:


       Yeah,  now you have to play the worst part  of this game. 
The "keyboard problem". I'm sure you asked ourselves how to find
a solution to that problem also before reading this text. 
       The problem isn't so simple,  so listen carefully.  There
are 2 chips on the motherboard that could really solve your pro-
blem, but the REAL problem is that you should use your soldering
iron with some VERY small pin.  Think that first you have to use 
a very very smaaaaall soldering iron and of course you must be a 
real solderings expert. 
       I didn't feel to be so expert,  so I took  my A1200 and I 
brought it in a centre of electronic repairs and assembling, and 
they did that work in almost 5 minutes.  I was astonished when I 
saw how those 3 wires were soldered on those smaaaaaall pins. If 
you  don't believe  they are so small,  take a look on the  main 
board and see! Before I opened A1200 case I was sure  I could do 
that work,  I was sure I could solder those wires,  but after  I 
opened it.... hmmmm... IMPOSSIBLE!!!
       Anyways, this is the scheme you have to follow not to ma-
ke mistakes and  get a  perfect  female DIN or PS2 connector for 
your keyboard. How you can see you have to  take 5 wires, CLOCK, 
DAT, RESET, GND and +5V.  For the keyboard you have just to con-
nect 4 of them (DAT, CLOCK GND and +5V), and the  KB RESET  must 
be connected to a switch (if your tower case has a RESET button, 
you can use it) with a GND signal (ground, so you can also use a 
simple wire connected to the same tower case ground). 
       Someone recently told me that he had to cut 2 pins on the
U13 micro. He had to do that because  the new  external keyboard
didn't work. Write me if someone  else of you find  this problem
too.        
                                    

